Michael Waldron CMSC320 final project: An analysis on the Universal Crime Report

Introduction

To begin: what is the Universal Crime Report (UCR)? According to the Federal Bureau of Investigation, the UCR is “the starting place for law enforcement executives, students of criminal justice, researchers, members of the media, and the public at large seeking information on crime in the nation” (https://ucr.fbi.gov/?came_from=https%3A//ucr.fbi.gov/word/). More specifically, the UCR is a conglomerate of crime reports sent to the FBI by state/local police to track some of the most serious and frequent crimes on a national scale. What serious and frequent crimes are isn’t given a clear definition. To explain both with an example, take notice of how kidnapping is not included in the UCR. While kidnapping is certainly a serious crime, it is so rare that national scale statistical analyses wouldn’t be meaningful. The crimes included in the UCR are as follows (legal definitions given below): criminal homicide, rape, robbery, aggravated assault, burglary, larceny, and motor vehicle theft. The UCR provides data for these crimes by state and year, both in total and as a rate of instances per 100,000 citizens.

This tutorial will cover obtaining UCR data, tidying the data to make testing simpler, and some experiments that can be done with the data. On the individual/general level, crime analyses with the UCR can help to answer questions many of us have about crime. Is crime getting worse? Is my state safe? What crimes are more likely where I am? In terms of data science on the whole, analysis on the UCR can have implications on crime policy nation wide, effect political campaigns (to fact check candidates who focus on crime), and illustrate the importance of good data collection habits.

On that note, it is important to mention while the UCR is definitively the best resource for public crime reporting, the UCR is not perfect and any analyses done with its data need to be taken with a grain of salt. See the insights section for elaboration on this point.

Data curation, parsing, and management

UCR data can be viewed and downloaded as a .csv file from https://www.bjs.gov/ucrdata/Search/Crime/State/StatebyState.cfm?NoVariables=Y&CFID=161469185&CFTOKEN=32f049d01284740-856CB110-E22D-C0F7-1F3DA2D25C6191F1. This website provides a tool that allows users to choose what data they would like to select - in terms of state, crime, and/or year. The data used in this tutorial includes all states, crimes, and years so that we can filter the data on our own if necessary.

Before loading the UCR data into RStudio, open the .csv in a text editor and remove all the information after the last numerical entry. This will make parsing the document much easier in the next couple steps. However, the file’s formatting is still flawed, so the read.csv() function will not work. Instead, use the readLines() function and remove all lines that contain any alphabetic symbols. Once this is done we can read a textConnection of what is left and assign relevant names to all of the columns. Finally, I created a vector in excel to add a state column to our data frame. Each state has 55 entries (1 for each year from 1960 to 2014) except New York which is missing data for the first 5 years. Because our data includes the US total and District of Columbia, there will be 2855 total entries. After adding this column I chose to rearrange the table, so the state and year would be the first attributes.

Exploratory data analysis

First let’s illustrate the importance of distinguishing between crime and crime rates.

UCR_df %>%
  filter(state == "US Total") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=homicide)) +
  geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Instances of homicide in the US")

UCR_df %>%
  filter(state == "US Total") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=homicide_rate)) +
  geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Rate of homicide in the US")

These graphs provide an example of how easily data can mislead its readers. In this instance, I can imagine a political candidate deliberately using the “Instances of homicide” graph to convince their constituents homicide in America hasn’t gotten significantly ‘better’ in the last 20 years. When in reality, the rate of homicide (which is the appropriate statistic to investigate in terms of reducing crime) has been on a relatively steady decline since the year 2000. Furthermore, these graphs illustrate how important it is to pay attention to the scale, as the homicide rate only varies between about 5 and 10 homicides per 100,000 citizens (so not that much).

Since we’ve discussed that great power comes with great responsibility, let’s see what we can do with our data.

Hypothesis testing

I’d like to do a correlation test to determine whether a state’s stance on the death penalty effects the rate of homicide. I will conduct this test both by individual state and on the national level over time. Our null hypothesis to test against for both is the absence of a relationship.

First, we need to add another column corresponding to whether each state has the death penalty at any given year. We will need to do this manually, but the information can be found here: https://deathpenaltyinfo.org/states-and-without-death-penalty. I began by adding an entire column labeled TRUE, then changed appropriate entries to FALSE based on if/when the state revoked the death penalty.

#Preparing the new data frame
death_df <- UCR_df %>%
  filter(state != "US Total") %>%
  subset(select = c(state,year, population, homicide, homicide_rate))

death_df$death_penalty <- TRUE

death_df <- death_df %>%

From these tests, we can conclude that (based upon the UCR data) there is no significant correlation between the death penalty and the rate of homicide when looking at each state individually, with averaged data from 1960-2014. However, when looking at national averages over time, there is a significant positive correlation between the death penalty and the rate of homicide. Meaning, the combined homicide rates of all states with the death penalty will reliably be higher than that of states without the death penalty. Note this is a test for correlation and not causation.

Machine learning

Now that we know there is a correlation between the number of states with/without the death penalty and homicide rate over time, let’s use cross validation to see how accurately we can predict whether a state has the death penalty using the mean homicide rate and year. I will compare both a logistic regression model and decision tree.

#This is an example of k-fold cross validation, with k=10
fold_indices <- cvFolds(n=nrow(death_by_year), K=10)

error_rates <- sapply(1:10, function(fold_index) {
  test_indices <- which(fold_indices$which == fold_index)
  test_set <- death_by_year[test_indices,] #[row=test_indices, columns=all]
  train_set <- death_by_year[-test_indices,]
  
  logis_fit <- glm(death_penalty~., data=train_set, family="binomial") #death_penalty~. <- predict y=death_penalty based upon all other variables (year, mean_homicide_rate)
  logis_pred <- ifelse(predict(logis_fit, newdata=test_set, type="response") > 0.5, 0,1)
  logis_error <- mean(test_set$death_penalty != logis_pred)
  
  tree_fit <- tree(as.factor(death_penalty)~., data=train_set)
  pruned_tree <- prune.tree(tree_fit, best=3)

  tree_pred <- predict(pruned_tree, newdata=test_set, type="class")
  tree_error <- mean(test_set$death_penalty != tree_pred)
  c(logis_error, tree_error)
  })

rownames(error_rates) <- c("logis", "tree")
error_rates <- as.data.frame(t(error_rates))

error_rates <- error_rates %>%
  mutate(fold=1:n()) %>%
  gather(method,error,-fold)

Of the two methods, neither is a great fit. Both have pretty significant error rates, and the logistic regression model has an impressively high variance. This would imply there are more variables at play than just death penalty policy in terms of a causal relationship for national homicide rate.

Insights

I’d like to begin with some criticisms of the UCR, addressing the grain of salt I alluded to in the introduction. The UCR only counts crime reports that are cleared by an arrest, meaning unsolved and unreported crime is not included in the data. However, attempted crime is included in the data, provided there was an arrest. The UCR is NOT mandatory, meaning even more data could be missing. Furthermore, because reporting data to the UCR is optional, and the responsibility of reporting falls to the local police, there have been cases of data being altered. Some police jurisdictions might have political motives for reporting more or less crime than actually took place (although this is very rare today). Another quirk of UCR data is reliant upon something called the hierarchy rule. The order in which I listed the crimes above is intentional, according to a hierarchy of perceived severity. The rule states that if multiple crimes are committed by the same person, only the crime with the highest severity will be recorded. One side effect of this is larceny of any kind is more severe than motor vehicle theft (according to the UCR) so if a criminal steals a pack of cigarettes from a store clerk, then steals a car to escape, the cigarette theft will be the only crime included in our data. Also, the value of the theft that occurred is not included in UCR data. Finally, federal crimes (such as bank robberies) are not included in the UCR. While the list of complaints does continue, these are the shortcomings I find most important to mention, in terms of data collection. I will also reiterate that while the UCR is far from perfect, it shouldn’t be ignored as the UCR is not without strengths. The most immediate strengths being the data is cheap to collect and free to access for anyone with an internet connection. Knowledge of these criticisms comes from my Criminological and Criminal Justice Research Methods class with Laure Brooks at UMD, but if any readers want to do their own research on how the UCR works this would be a good place to start: https://www.ncjrs.gov/App/Publications/abstract.aspx?ID=93896.

With criticisms out of the way, I feel we have learned quite a bit from our data. We learned it is important to distinguish between crime and crime rate. Delaware was a pretty scary place in 1993, forgetting to lock your door in the Dakota’s will probably go unpunished, and there is always more property (non-violent) crime than violent crime. We learned the distribution of sex crime nation wide and that assault is the most common violent crime in every state but Ohio. We discovered a highly significant correlation between death states grouped by death penalty policy and their respective homicide rates and that the correlation is not great for making predictions. And there is so much more to learn from this data, especially as I focused mainly on violent crime, but hopefully this tutorial was sufficient enough for anyone to adapt my code and answer further questions on their own, as both the data set and RStudio are free.

Definitions

The following is copied exactly from https://www.ucrdatatool.gov/offenses.cfm

Criminal Homicide: a.) Murder and nonnegligent manslaughter: the willful (nonnegligent) killing of one human being by another. Deaths caused by negligence, attempts to kill, assaults to kill, suicides, and accidental deaths are excluded. The program classifies justifiable homicides separately and limits the definition to: (1) the killing of a felon by a law enforcement officer in the line of duty; or (2) the killing of a felon, during the commission of a felony, by a private citizen. b.) Manslaughter by negligence: the killing of another person through gross negligence. Deaths of persons due to their own negligence, accidental deaths not resulting from gross negligence, and traffic fatalities are not included in the category Manslaughter by Negligence.

Forcible Rape/Legacy Rape: The carnal knowledge of a female forcibly and against her will. Rapes by force and attempts or assaults to rape, regardless of the age of the victim, are included. Statutory offenses (no force used-victim under age of consent) are excluded.

Revised Rape: Penetration, no matter how slight, of the vagina or anus with any body part or object, or oral penetration by a sex organ of another person, without the consent of the victim. Attempts or assaults to commit rape are also included; however, statutory rape and incest are excluded. In December 2011, the UCR program changed its definition of SRS rape to this revised definition. This change can be seen in the UCR data starting in 2013. Any data reported under the older definition of rape will be called “legacy rape”.

Robbery: The taking or attempting to take anything of value from the care, custody, or control of a person or persons by force or threat of force or violence and/or by putting the victim in fear.

Aggravated assault: An unlawful attack by one person upon another for the purpose of inflicting severe or aggravated bodily injury. This type of assault usually is accompanied by the use of a weapon or by means likely to produce death or great bodily harm. Simple assaults are excluded.

Burglary (breaking or entering): The unlawful entry of a structure to commit a felony or a theft. Attempted forcible entry is included.

Larceny: The unlawful taking, carrying, leading, or riding away of property from the possession or constructive possession of another. Examples are thefts of bicycles, motor vehicle parts and accessories, shoplifting, pocketpicking, or the stealing of any property or article that is not taken by force and violence or by fraud. Attempted larcenies are included. Embezzlement, confidence games, forgery, check fraud, etc., are excluded.

Motor Vehicle Theft: The theft or attempted theft of a motor vehicle. A motor vehicle is self-propelled and runs on land surface and not on rails. Motorboats, construction equipment, airplanes, and farming equipment are specifically excluded from this category.
